from __future__ import annotations

import plotly.graph_objects as go
from shared import df, plot_timeseries, value_box_server, value_box_ui
from shiny import App, Inputs, Outputs, Session, reactive, ui
from shinywidgets import output_widget, render_plotly
from faicons import icon_svg

all_attributes = ["OXIDO", "FIBRA", "EXPANSORAPG", "AGUA"]
y = ui.card("A simple card")

app_ui = ui.page_sidebar(
    ui.sidebar(
        ui.input_checkbox_group("atributos", "Atributos", all_attributes, selected=all_attributes)
    ),
    ui.layout_columns(
        value_box_ui("OXIDO", "Oxido"),
        value_box_ui("FIBRA", "Fibra"),
        value_box_ui("EXPANSORAPG", "Expansor"),
        value_box_ui("AGUA", "Agua"),
        fill=False,
        id="value-boxes",
    ),
    ui.card(
        ui.card_header(
            "Atributos en el tiempo",
            ui.input_switch("pause", "Pause updates", value=False, width="auto"),
            class_="d-flex justify-content-between",
        ),
        output_widget("plot"),
        full_screen=True,
    ),
    ui.hr(),
    ui.layout_column_wrap(y,y,width="250px", height="350px"),

    title="Model monitoring dashboard",
    class_="bslib-page-dashboard",
)

def server(input: Inputs, output: Outputs, session: Session):
    # Note that df from shared.py is a reactive calc that gets
    # invalidated (approximately) when the database updates
    # We can choose to ignore the invalidation by doing an isolated read
    @reactive.calc
    def maybe_paused_df():
        if not input.pause():
            return df()
        with reactive.isolate():
            return df()

    # Source the value box module server code for each model
    for atributo in all_attributes:
        value_box_server(atributo, maybe_paused_df, atributo)

    # Create an empty plotly figure on page load
    @render_plotly
    def plot():
        return go.FigureWidget()

    # Update the plotly figure with the latest data
    @reactive.effect
    def _():
        d = maybe_paused_df()
        d = d[d["Atributo"].isin(input.atributos())]
        with plot.widget.batch_animate():
            fig = plot_timeseries(d)
            plot.widget.update(layout=fig.layout, data=fig.data)

    # Hacky way to hide/show model value boxes. This is currently the only real
    # option you want the value box UI to be statically rendered (thus, reducing
    # flicker on update), but also want to hide/show them based on user input.
    @reactive.effect
    @reactive.event(input.atributos)
    def _():
        ui.remove_ui("#value-box-hide")  # Remove any previously added style tag

        # Construct CSS to hide the value boxes that the user has deselected
        css = ""
        missing_atributes = list(set(all_attributes) - set(input.atributos()))
        for atributo in missing_atributes:
            i = all_attributes.index(atributo) + 1
            css += f"#value-boxes > *:nth-child({i}) {{ display: none; }}"

        # Add the CSS to the head of the document
        if css:
            style = ui.tags.style(css, id="value-box-hide")
            ui.insert_ui(style, selector="head")

app = App(app_ui, server)

import asyncio
import datetime
import random
import sqlite3
from pathlib import Path

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

here = Path(__file__).parent
scores_ = pd.read_csv(here / "PruebaSQC.csv")
excluded_columns = ['INICIO','FIN','Bitacora','Turno','Operador','Estacion','Maquina','Producto','Formato','PLACA','ACIDO','DENSIDAD','PENETRACION','HUMEDAD', 'TAMB', 'HAMB','COMENTARIOS']
scores_ = scores_.drop(columns=excluded_columns)
scores_ = scores_.dropna(subset=['OXIDO'])
scores_ = pd.melt(scores_, id_vars=['Fecha'], var_name= 'Atributo', value_name= 'Valor')
scores_ = scores_.drop_duplicates(subset=['Fecha', 'Atributo'])
scores_['Fecha'] = pd.to_datetime(scores_['Fecha'], format='%d/%m/%Y')
scores_ = scores_.sort_values(by='Fecha')
scores_['Index'] = scores_.groupby('Fecha').ngroup() + 1
scores_.set_index("Index", inplace = True)
(here / "data").mkdir(exist_ok=True)

SQLITE_DB_URI = f"file:{here / 'data' /'scores.sqlite'}"

def init_db():
    with sqlite3.connect(SQLITE_DB_URI, uri=True, timeout=30) as con:
        con.execute("PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL")
        con.execute("drop table if exists scores")

        now = datetime.datetime.utcnow()
        position = now.minute * 60 + now.second + 1

        # Simulate 100 seconds of historical data
        offset_secs = -np.arange(100) - 1
        
        abs_secs = (position + offset_secs) % (60 * 60) + 1
        initial_scores = scores_.loc[abs_secs]
        timestamps = pd.DataFrame(
            {
                "timestamp": now + pd.to_timedelta(offset_secs, unit="s"),
                "second": abs_secs,
            }
        ).set_index("second", inplace=False)
        initial_scores = initial_scores.join(timestamps, how="left")
        initial_scores.to_sql("scores", con, index=False, if_exists="append")

        con.execute(
            "create index idx_scores_timestamp on scores(timestamp)"
        )
        return position
    
async def update_db(position):
    with sqlite3.connect(SQLITE_DB_URI, uri=True, timeout=30) as con:
        while True:
            new_data = scores_.loc[position].copy()
            new_data["timestamp"] = datetime.datetime.utcnow()
            new_data.to_sql("scores", con, index=False, if_exists="append")
            position = (position % (60 * 60)) + 1
            await asyncio.sleep(random.randint(2, 4))

#async def update_db(position):
    try:
        with sqlite3.connect(SQLITE_DB_URI, uri=True, timeout=60) as con:
            while True:
                if position in scores_.index:
                    new_data = scores_.loc[position].copy()
                    new_data["timestamp"] = datetime.datetime.now()
                    print(new_data)  # Debugging output
                    new_data.to_sql("scores", con, index=False, if_exists="append")
                    position = (position % (60 * 60)) + 1
                    await asyncio.sleep(random.randint(2, 4))
                else:
                    print(f"Position {position} not in index")
                    break
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error updating database: {e}")

    


"""     try: 
        loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()
    except RuntimeError:
        loop = asyncio.new_event_loop()
        asyncio.set_event_loop(loop)
        loop.run_forever()
    
    asyncio.create_task(update_db(position)) """
def begin():
    position = init_db()
    if asyncio.get_event_loop().is_running():
        asyncio.create_task(update_db(position))
    else: 
        from threading import Thread

        Thread(target=lambda: asyncio.run(update_db(position)), daemon=True).start()

import sqlite3

import faicons as fa
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

import scoredata
from shiny import module, reactive, render, ui

scoredata.begin()
con = sqlite3.connect(scoredata.SQLITE_DB_URI, uri=True)

def last_modified():
    """
    Fast-executing call to get the timestamp of the most recent row in the
    database. We will poll against this in absence of a way to receive a push
    notification when our SQLite database changes.
    """
    res = con.execute("select max(timestamp) from scores")
    return res.fetchone()[0]

@reactive.poll(last_modified)
def df():
    """
    @reactive.poll calls a cheap query (`last_modified()`) every 1 second to
    check if the expensive query (`df()`) should be run and downstream
    calculations should be updated.

    By declaring this reactive object at the top-level of the script instead of
    in the server function, all sessions are sharing the same object, so the
    expensive query is only run once no matter how many users are connected.
    """
    tbl = pd.read_sql(
        "select * from scores order by timestamp desc, Atributo desc limit ?",
        con,
        params=[150],
    )

    # Convert timestamp to datetime object, which SQLite doesn't support natively
    tbl["timestamp"] = pd.to_datetime(tbl["timestamp"], utc=True)
    # Create a short label for readability
    tbl["time"] = tbl["timestamp"].dt.strftime("%H:%M:%S")
    # Reverse order of rows
    tbl = tbl.iloc[::-1]

    return tbl


# -------------------------------------
# Plot and value box logic
# -------------------------------------

THRESHOLD_HIGH = 1085
THRESHOLD_HIGH_COLOR = "#f9b928"
THRESHOLD_LOW = 1080
THRESHOLD_LOW_COLOR = "#c10000"

@module.ui
def value_box_ui(title):
    return ui.value_box(
        title,
        ui.output_text("value"),
        showcase=ui.output_ui("icon"),
    )

@module.server
def value_box_server(input, output, session, df, atributo: str):
    @reactive.calc
    def score():
        d = df()
        filtered_df = d[d["Atributo"] == atributo]
        if not filtered_df.empty:
            return filtered_df.iloc[-1]["Valor"]
        else:
            return 0  # or some default value
    
    @render.text
    def value():
        return f"{score():.2f}"
    
    @render.ui
    def icon():
        if score() > THRESHOLD_HIGH:
            return fa.icon_svg("circle-exclamation").add_class("text-danger")
        if score() < THRESHOLD_LOW:
            return fa.icon_svg("circle-exclamation").add_class("text-danger")
        return fa.icon_svg("circle-check").add_class("text-success")

    
def plot_timeseries(d):
    fig = px.line(
        d,
        x="time",
        y="Valor",
        labels=dict(score="accuracy"),
        color="Atributo",
        color_discrete_sequence=px.colors.qualitative.Set2,
        template="simple_white",
        markers= True,
    )

    fig.add_hline(
        THRESHOLD_HIGH,
        line_dash="dot",
        line=dict(color=THRESHOLD_HIGH_COLOR, width=2),
        opacity=0.3,
        annotation=dict(text="USL", xref="paper", x=1, y=THRESHOLD_HIGH),
        annotation_position="top right",
    )

    fig.add_hline(
        THRESHOLD_LOW,
        line_dash="dot",
        line=dict(color=THRESHOLD_LOW_COLOR, width=2),
        opacity=0.3,
        annotation=dict(text="LSL", xref="paper", x=1, y=THRESHOLD_LOW),
        annotation_position="bottom right",
    )

    fig.update_yaxes(range=[1050, 1100], fixedrange=True)
    fig.update_xaxes(fixedrange=True, tickangle=60)
    fig.update_layout(hovermode="x unified")

    return fig
